-- ── GetResponse ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$GetResponse is a Poland-based all-in-one online marketing platform combining email marketing, marketing automation, landing pages, and e-commerce tools for small and mid-sized businesses.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (paid plans from about $19/month)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1998, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$400-500 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Gdansk, Poland$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$Polish$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Russian$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$GetResponse Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$GetResponse review 2026: email marketing, automation, landing pages and pricing plans compared. See features, pros, cons and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$GetResponse is a long-running email marketing and online marketing automation platform headquartered in Gdansk, Poland. Its origin story is one of the oldest in the email marketing industry: in 1997, a 17-year-old Polish entrepreneur named Simon Grabowski was running a small travel listings site called Travel Poland and grew frustrated with manually emailing updates to subscribers. He wrote a script to automate the process, which he initially commercialized as a product called Implix before relaunching it under the GetResponse brand around 1998. That makes GetResponse one of the first dedicated email marketing automation tools built in Europe, predating many of its now better-known American competitors. Grabowski has remained CEO and largest shareholder for the company's entire history, and GetResponse has grown into a bootstrapped, privately held SaaS business without taking outside venture funding, reportedly surpassing $150 million in annual revenue and serving several hundred thousand customers across more than 180 countries, with a workforce in the 400-500 employee range spread across offices in Poland, the United States, Belarus, Ukraine, Malta, and elsewhere.

Product-wise, GetResponse has expanded well beyond its original email-blast roots into a broader marketing suite. Core capabilities include drag-and-drop email design, autoresponder sequences, visual marketing automation workflows with conditional logic, list segmentation and behavioral targeting, landing page and website building tools, conversion funnels for e-commerce and lead generation, webinar hosting, a course-creation module for selling digital products, paid newsletter and subscription tools, SMS marketing, web push notifications, and, more recently, AI-assisted content generation for subject lines, email copy, and full campaigns. This breadth means GetResponse competes not only with pure email tools like Mailchimp and Constant Contact but also with funnel-and-automation platforms like ActiveCampaign, Klaviyo, and even course platforms like Kajabi and Teachable, positioning itself as an 'all-in-one' alternative so smaller businesses do not need to stitch together several separate subscriptions.

GetResponse's pricing is structured around contact list size and feature tier rather than flat per-seat pricing, and it is one of the few major email platforms that still offers a genuinely usable free plan (for very small lists, capped features, and a single user) alongside a 30-day free trial of paid tiers with no credit card required. Paid plans begin with Starter (list-priced around $19 per month for the smallest contact volume when billed monthly, cheaper on annual billing), which includes unlimited monthly email sends, limited AI content generation, one automation workflow, a landing page builder, and support for up to three team members. The Marketer plan is the most popular tier and unlocks unlimited automation workflows, advanced segmentation, abandoned cart recovery, sales funnels, promo codes, revenue reporting, and unlimited web push notifications for up to five users. The Creator plan adds a paid course creator (up to roughly 500 students), premium newsletter subscriptions, a website builder, and webinar hosting for up to 100 attendees. At the top, GetResponse Max/Enterprise is custom-priced and adds SMS marketing credits, mobile push notifications, a dedicated sending domain and IP address, a dedicated customer experience manager, and priority phone and Slack support with unlimited users. Annual billing typically saves customers around 18% versus paying monthly.

GetResponse targets small businesses, solo creators, coaches, e-commerce merchants, and marketing teams at mid-sized companies who want a single platform to run email campaigns, build simple websites or funnels, and automate customer journeys without hiring a dedicated marketing-ops team. Its e-commerce integrations (Shopify, WooCommerce, PrestaShop, Magento) and abandoned-cart tooling make it particularly popular with online retailers, while its webinar and course tools appeal to solo educators and consultants. Deliverability, ease of use, and price-to-feature ratio are frequently cited strengths in third-party reviews, while some reviewers note that its automation builder and reporting are less sophisticated than dedicated enterprise marketing-automation suites like HubSpot or Marketo, and that its interface can feel dated compared to newer entrants. Overall, GetResponse's differentiation is longevity, an unusually wide feature set for the price, and a genuinely free entry tier, which keeps it competitive against both legacy email marketing incumbents and newer AI-first marketing tools.

One notable part of GetResponse's history is that it grew almost entirely without outside capital during the early web era, at a time when most of its now-larger American rivals were still small startups themselves; Grabowski has spoken publicly about bootstrapping the company from that original $200 in savings into a multi-hundred-employee, revenue-generating business spanning offices on multiple continents. That independence has arguably shaped GetResponse's product strategy, favoring steady feature accretion (webinars, then courses, then AI writing tools) over the kind of aggressive, VC-funded feature races seen at newer competitors. For buyers comparing platforms, GetResponse is frequently shortlisted alongside Mailchimp and Brevo for small-business email marketing, alongside ActiveCampaign and Klaviyo when automation depth and e-commerce personalization matter more, and alongside Kajabi or Teachable specifically for its course-creation and webinar bundle. Its pricing structure, tied to contact list size with unlimited sends included on every paid tier, also differs meaningfully from send-volume-based competitors, which can make GetResponse comparatively cheaper for businesses that email frequently but keep a moderate list size, and comparatively pricier for businesses with very large but rarely-emailed lists.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '83a31e14-8b81-4e6f-bd44-bf1082ccd21f';

