-- ── GIMP ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$GIMP (GNU Image Manipulation Program) is a free, open-source, cross-platform raster graphics editor used for photo retouching, image composition, and digital painting, positioned as a free alternative to Adobe Photoshop.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1995, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Volunteer-driven open-source project (no formal company)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$Italian$q$, $q$Japanese$q$, $q$Russian$q$, $q$Chinese$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$, $q$Dutch$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$GIMP Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$GIMP review 2026: the free, open-source Photoshop alternative. Explore features, version history, pros, cons and the best GIMP alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$GIMP, short for the GNU Image Manipulation Program, is one of the longest-running and most widely used free and open-source raster graphics editors in existence. It began in 1995 as a class project by two University of California, Berkeley computer science students, Spencer Kimball and Peter Mattis, who were working at the school's eXperimental Computing Facility. As the origin story is often told, rather than complete an assigned compiler-writing project in Scheme/Lisp for a course taught by professor Richard Fateman, the pair decided to build an image manipulation program instead. They originally called it the General Image Manipulation Program and coined the acronym GIMP by prefixing 'G' to '-IMP', a naming choice reportedly influenced by the character 'the gimp' from the 1994 film Pulp Fiction. The first public release, version 0.54, shipped in January 1996 and already included a plug-in architecture that let outside developers extend the program without touching its core code, a design decision that shaped GIMP's extensibility culture from the very beginning.

A pivotal moment in GIMP's history came in 1997, when Kimball and Mattis met Richard Stallman, founder of the GNU Project and the Free Software Foundation, during a visit to Berkeley. They asked whether they could rename 'General' to 'GNU' to formally affiliate the project with the GNU operating system, and Stallman agreed, officially making it the GNU Image Manipulation Program under the GNU General Public License. This affiliation cemented GIMP's identity as flagship free-software image-editing tool and helped it attract a growing volunteer developer community as Kimball and Mattis graduated and moved on to other projects, handing long-term stewardship of GIMP to the broader open-source community that has maintained and expanded it ever since. Development of GIMP also directly gave rise to GTK (originally the GIMP Toolkit), the widget toolkit built to support GIMP's user interface needs, which subsequently became a foundational GUI toolkit used far beyond GIMP itself, powering GNOME and countless other Linux desktop applications.

GIMP is licensed under the GNU General Public License version 3 or later, making it completely free to download, use, modify, and redistribute, with no paid tiers, subscriptions, or feature restrictions of any kind, in explicit contrast to Adobe Photoshop's subscription-only Creative Cloud model. It is available natively on Windows, macOS, and Linux/BSD systems, with community-maintained ports and packages across virtually every major desktop platform. Major version milestones include GIMP 1.0 in 1998, GIMP 2.0 in 2004, GIMP 2.8 in 2012 (which introduced single-window mode), GIMP 2.10 in 2018 (which brought GEGL-based high-bit-depth color processing and non-destructive editing groundwork), and, after a notably long development cycle, GIMP 3.0 in March 2025, which finally delivered full non-destructive editing, GTK3-based UI modernization, and improved support for modern file formats. A subsequent 3.2 release in 2026 added further capabilities including link layers and expanded vector layer support, showing the project remains actively developed nearly three decades after its founding.

Functionally, GIMP offers a feature set comparable in scope to professional commercial image editors: layer-based compositing with layer masks and blend modes, advanced selection tools including Bezier-curve-based paths, retouching and cloning tools, color correction and channel manipulation, roughly 150 built-in filters and effects, and support for a very wide range of file formats including its own native XCF format alongside JPEG, PNG, WebP, GIF, TIFF, PSD (Photoshop) import/export, and more. Its scripting and automation system supports Script-Fu (a Scheme dialect), along with Python, Perl, and Tcl bindings, enabling batch processing and custom tool development, and its plug-in architecture has spawned a large ecosystem of third-party extensions and filters (including the well-known G'MIC filter collection). GIMP's official mascot, a bird-like figure named Wilber, was itself created using GIMP in 1997 and remains an emblem of the project's self-referential open-source culture.

GIMP's target audience spans hobbyist photographers and digital artists, students and educators who need professional-grade tools without licensing costs, open-source and Linux-first users, and budget-conscious freelancers or small studios who cannot justify an ongoing Adobe Creative Cloud subscription. Because there is no formal parent company, GIMP has no headquarters, no employee count, and no venture funding; it is sustained entirely by volunteer maintainers, individual and organizational donations, and contributions coordinated through its official GNOME-affiliated infrastructure and GitLab-hosted repository. Its most direct competitor is Adobe Photoshop, against which it is constantly benchmarked in the free-vs-paid image editing conversation, along with other tools such as Affinity Photo (a one-time-purchase commercial alternative), Krita (which is more painting-focused), Photopea (a browser-based Photoshop-like editor), and Paint.NET. GIMP's core differentiation is that it is entirely free, fully open source, and cross-platform with no recurring costs, at the tradeoff of a steeper learning curve and a less streamlined, less 'polished' user experience than modern commercial competitors, along with historically slower adoption of features like full non-destructive editing that Adobe has offered for longer.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '05fd9154-b81e-4108-87a9-fd64b03f828c';

