-- ── Gitea ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gitea is a lightweight, self-hostable, MIT-licensed Git service offering code hosting, issue tracking, pull requests, CI/CD, and package registry features, forked from Gogs in 2016 and also available as the managed Gitea Cloud.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source (self-hosted) with paid Enterprise and Cloud tiers$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted); Enterprise/Cloud from about $9.50/user/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$1-20 employees (Gitea Limited) plus a large open-source contributor community$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Hamburg, Germany$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$, $q$German$q$, $q$Chinese$q$, $q$Spanish$q$, $q$French$q$, $q$Japanese$q$, $q$Russian$q$, $q$Portuguese$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gitea Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gitea review 2026: self-hosted Git service features, Gitea Cloud pricing, and how it compares to GitHub, GitLab and the Forgejo fork.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gitea is a lightweight, self-hostable Git forge providing code hosting, issue tracking, pull requests, CI/CD, wikis, and package registry functionality, released under the MIT license. It began life as a fork of Gogs, another self-hosted Git service written in Go, in November 2016. The fork was driven by community frustration that Gogs, despite being open source, was tightly controlled by a single maintainer whose decisions on merging contributions and project direction were seen by parts of the community as a bottleneck; a group of Gogs contributors forked the codebase specifically to establish a community-driven governance model with a broader group of maintainers making decisions collectively rather than one individual. The newly forked project shipped its first official 1.0 release in December 2016, and from there grew steadily as a popular, resource-efficient alternative to heavier self-hosted Git platforms like GitLab.

For its first several years, Gitea operated purely as a community open-source project without a formal company behind it, governed by its maintainer group and funded through Open Collective donations. That changed in October 2022, when two of the project's most prominent maintainers, Lunny Xiao and Matti Ranta, founded a for-profit company, Gitea Limited, headquartered in Hamburg, Germany, with the explicit goal of building commercial hosting and enterprise offerings on top of the open-source project, including specialized closed-source components for paying customers. This move proved controversial within the broader Gitea community: because it appeared to shift governance and commercial control toward a private company using the open-source project's brand and codebase without a fully transparent community process, a significant portion of contributors and users objected. In response, the nonprofit hosting platform Codeberg led an effort to fork Gitea into a new, community-governed project called Forgejo in late 2022, explicitly positioning itself as a 'soft fork' that would remain community-owned and resist any future commercialization of the kind that prompted its creation. Both Gitea and Forgejo have continued to be actively developed since the split, with Forgejo occasionally diverging on governance and some features while both remain largely compatible, MIT/GPL-licensed, Go-based Git forges.

Technically, Gitea is written primarily in Go with a TypeScript-based frontend, designed deliberately to be lightweight and resource-efficient enough to run on very modest hardware, including a Raspberry Pi, which has made it popular among individual developers, small teams, and self-hosting enthusiasts who find GitLab's resource footprint excessive for their needs. It supports cross-platform deployment on Linux, macOS, Windows, and the BSDs, and can be installed via Docker, a single binary, or various package managers. Feature-wise, the free, self-hosted, MIT-licensed core includes Git-based code hosting, issue tracking, pull request review, a project/kanban-style management board, a wiki, Gitea Actions (Gitea's own CI/CD system modeled after GitHub Actions workflow syntax), and a built-in package registry supporting multiple package formats, all with unlimited users and repositories at no cost, a stark contrast to GitHub's and GitLab's tiered user-count-based pricing on their own free plans.

Alongside the free self-hosted core, Gitea Limited monetizes through two commercial products layered on top of the open-source base. Gitea Enterprise is a self-managed offering priced per user per month (publicly listed in the roughly $9.50 to $19 per user per month range, with online-payment customers required to commit to a one-year term), which adds SAML SSO integration, audit logs, Kubernetes-based autoscaling CI/CD runners, priority security notifications, email and online support with a service-level agreement, installation assistance, and emergency phone support, with discounts available for nonprofits and small companies. Gitea Cloud is the company's fully managed hosting product, letting customers choose their preferred cloud provider and region while Gitea Limited handles infrastructure, unlimited network traffic, zero-maintenance automatic upgrades, and professional business support, with additional object storage billed at roughly $10 per 100GB; a 30-day free trial is available for prospective Cloud customers.

Gitea's target audience spans individual developers and small teams who want a genuinely free, lightweight, self-hosted Git platform; organizations that need more governance, compliance, and support features than the open-source core provides but still want to self-manage their infrastructure (served by Gitea Enterprise); and teams that want Gitea's feature set without operating any infrastructure themselves (served by Gitea Cloud). Its most direct competitors are GitHub and GitLab as the dominant hosted Git platforms, self-hosted GitLab Community/Enterprise Edition as a heavier but more feature-rich self-hosted alternative, and its own sibling fork Forgejo as the community-governed option for users specifically wary of Gitea Limited's commercial direction. Gitea's core differentiation remains its lightweight resource footprint, straightforward MIT-licensed free tier with no artificial user or repository caps, and a maturing set of paid enterprise and cloud options for organizations that outgrow pure self-hosting, though the 2022 commercialization and subsequent Forgejo fork mean prospective adopters weighing Gitea specifically for its community-governance reputation should be aware of that history.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'b8e10e1d-f374-4ec0-aa21-3a07fe66eae5';

